      <h1 style="margin-top:14px">Understanding kidney disease &amp; ESRD</h1>
      <p class="lead">A gentle overview for patients and families who've just heard the words “kidney disease.”</p>
      <p class="muted" style="font-size:.9rem">Adapted with permission from
        <a href={src}>renalcarematters.com</a>.</p>

      <h2>What your kidneys do</h2>
      <p>Your two kidneys quietly filter about <strong>200 litres of blood every day</strong> — removing
      waste and extra fluid, balancing salts, helping control your blood pressure, and making hormones
      that support your blood and your bones. When they work, you never notice them. That's the point.</p>

      <h2>What “chronic kidney disease” means</h2>
      <p>Chronic kidney disease (CKD) means that filtering ability is slowly — and often silently —
      declining, over three months or more. It's found through <strong>blood tests, urine tests and
      imaging</strong>, not by how you feel: many people with early CKD feel completely normal. Unlike a
      sudden kidney injury, which can recover, CKD usually reflects lasting change, so the goal is to
      <strong>slow it down</strong> and protect what you have.</p>

      <h2>Knowing your stage (eGFR)</h2>
      <p>The key number is your <strong>eGFR</strong> — think of it as the percentage of your kidneys'
      filtering capacity still working. A healthy eGFR is above 90. CKD is grouped into five stages based
      on this number. The encouraging part: with early, steady treatment, <strong>many people stay in the
      earlier stages for decades</strong>.</p>

      <h2>Why it happens — and the heart link</h2>
      <p>About <strong>1 in 10 Filipinos</strong> has CKD, and most cases are driven by
      <strong>diabetes and high blood pressure</strong>, which slowly damage the kidneys' tiny filters.
      Kidney and heart health are closely tied — which is why your doctor watches your blood pressure,
      blood sugar and heart together, not in isolation.</p>

      <h2>What ESRD and dialysis are</h2>
      <p>End-stage renal disease (ESRD) is the point where the kidneys can no longer do enough on their
      own. <strong>Dialysis</strong> is a treatment that does part of their job — cleaning the blood and
      removing extra fluid — usually a few times each week.</p>

      <div class="notice"><strong>The reassuring part:</strong> many people live active, meaningful lives
      on dialysis — working, travelling and spending time with family. With good care, treatment becomes
      a routine, not a fear.</div>

